f his lowercase g does not fully close. Derivatives of Baskerville are often identified thus. A modern revival of Baskerville, a font called Mrs Eaves, is named after Baskerville\'s wife who was the widow of Richard Eaves.\r\n(From: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_Western_typography)'),(4865,114,2,7,0,'Photo'),(2660,119,3,74,0,'8'),(2661,119,3,73,0,'591'),(2662,119,3,72,0,'500'),(3550,115,2,48,0,'Wikipedia'),(3551,115,2,40,0,'1954'),(3552,115,2,37,0,'Sherbyte'),(3553,115,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Thu Nov 08 2012 18:15:37 GMT-0800 (PST)</description></Folder></kml>||||osm\r\nParis, France'),(3549,115,2,39,0,'Adrian Frutiger'),(3546,115,2,50,0,'\"Univers\"'),(3547,115,2,49,0,'Typefaces'),(3548,115,2,41,0,'\"Univers (French pronunciation: [ynivɛʁ], \"ünivair\") is the name of a realist sans-serif typeface designed by Adrian Frutiger in 1954.\"-Wikipedia'),(4862,114,2,37,0,'emoticon1234'),(4861,114,2,40,0,'1772'),(4859,114,2,39,0,'John Baskerville'),(4860,114,2,48,0,'http://www.dipity.com/emoticon1234/Graphic-Design-History/ (Accessed: 8 November 2012)'),(4856,114,2,50,0,'\"Baskerville\"'),(2681,120,3,74,0,'8'),(2682,120,3,73,0,'591'),(2683,120,3,72,0,'500'),(3545,116,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Thu Nov 08 2012 18:22:30 GMT-0800 (PST)</description></Folder></kml>||||osm\r\nBerlin, Germany'),(3541,116,2,39,0,'Günter Gerhard Lange'),(3542,116,2,48,0,'Wikipedia'),(3543,116,2,40,0,'1896'),(3544,116,2,37,0,'Jim Hood'),(3538,116,2,50,0,'\"Akzidenz-Grotesk\"'),(3539,116,2,49,0,'Typefaces'),(3540,116,2,41,0,'\"Akzidenz-Grotesk is a grotesque (early sans-serif) typeface originally released by the Berthold Type Foundry in 1896 under the name Accidenz-Grotesk. It was the first sans serif typeface to be widely used[citation needed] and influenced many later neo-grotesque typefaces after 1950.\"-Wikipedia'),(2692,121,3,74,0,'8'),(2693,121,3,73,0,'468'),(2694,121,3,72,0,'396'),(4091,117,2,7,0,'Photo'),(4085,117,2,39,0,'William Starling Burgess'),(4086,117,2,48,0,'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Times_New_Roman (Accessed: 8 November 2012)'),(4087,117,2,40,0,'1931'),(4088,117,2,37,0,'Wikipedia user: Rbpolsen'),(4089,117,2,42,0,'Image'),(4090,117,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Thu Nov 08 2012 18:23:44 GMT-0800 (Pacific Standard Time)</description></Folder></kml>||||osm\r\nAmerica'),(4082,117,2,50,0,'\"Times New Roman\"'),(4083,117,2,49,0,'Graphic design (Typography)--History'),(4084,117,2,41,0,'Times New Roman is a serif typeface commissioned by the British newspaper The Times in 1931, created by Victor Lardent at the English branch of Monotype. It was commissioned after Stanley Morison had written an article criticizing The Times for being badly printed and typographically antiquated. The font was supervised by Morison and drawn by Victor Lardent, an artist from the advertising department of The Times. Morison used an older font named Plantin as the basis for his design, but made revisions for legibility and economy of space. Morison\'s revision became known as Times New Roman and made its debut in the 3 October 1932 issue of The Times newspaper. After one year, the design was released for commercial sale. The Times stayed with Times New Roman for 40 years, but new production techniques and the format change from broadsheet to tabloid in 2004 have caused the newspaper to switch font five times since 1972. However, all the new fonts have been variants of the original New Roman font.\r\n(From: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Times_New_Roman)'),(4168,34,2,48,0,'http://calligraphy-expo.com/eng/AboutCalligraphy/Writing/FromTheDepthOfAges.aspx?ItemID=1413 (Accessed: 25 October 2012)'),(4169,34,2,40,0,'700'),(4166,34,2,49,0,'Graphic design (Typography)--History'),(4167,34,2,41,0,'Visigothic script was a type of medieval script that originated in the Visigothic kingdom in Hispania (the Iberian Peninsula, modern Spain and Portugal). Its more limiting alternative designations littera toletana and littera mozarabica associate it with scriptoria specifically in Toledo and with Mozarabic culture more generally, respectively.\r\nThe script, which exists in book-hand and cursive versions, was used from approximately the late seventh century until the thirteenth century, mostly in Visigothic Iberia but also somewhat in southern France. It was perfected in the 9th-11th centuries and declined afterwards. It developed from uncial script, and shares many features of uncial, especially an uncial form of the letter g.\r\n(From: http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Visigothic_script)'),(2743,122,3,74,0,'8'),(2744,122,3,73,0,'119'),(2745,122,3,72,0,'239'),(3999,24,2,41,0,'A website dedicated to typography and its history, notably featuring an interactive display of the fundamental aspects of the type anatomy.'),(3998,24,2,50,0,'Counter Space'),(2751,123,3,74,0,'8'),(2752,123,3,73,0,'578'),(2753,123,3,72,0,'632'),(3902,61,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Tue Nov 06 2012 07:47:00 GMT-0800 (PST)</description></Folder></kml>||||osm\r\nWorld Wide Web'),(2762,124,3,74,0,'8'),(2763,124,3,73,0,'256'),(2764,124,3,72,0,'296'),(3526,118,2,38,0,'<kml xmlns=\"http://earth.google.com/kml/2.0\"><Folder><name>OpenLayers export</name><description>Exported on Thu Nov 08 2012 19:42:56 GMT-0800 (PST)</description></Folder></kml>||||osm\r\nN/A'),(3527,118,2,7,0,'http://papress.com/thinkingwithtype/index.htm'),(3525,118,2,37,0,'Iman Salehian'),(3522,118,2,39,0,'Ellen Lupton'),(3523,118,2,48,0,'Thinking With Type'),(3524,118,2,40,0,'2007-11-28'),(3520,118,2,49,0,'Basics Typography'),(3521,118,2,41,0,'Screencap of, Thinking with Type: This site is the on-line companion to the book Thinking with Type: A Critical G