INSERT INTO `omeka_items_section_pages` VALUES (1,NULL,1,'<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/febe60b2fde5c9afff21a7f31f334e3b.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Old Style (occasionally referred to as Humanist) typefaces are based on hand lettering of scribes and they first appeared in the late 15th century.&nbsp;Their relation to calligraphy can be seen in the <strong>curved strokes</strong> and letters with <strong>subtle thick to thin transitions</strong>, looking somewhat like letters drawn with a pen and ink. The serifs on Old Styles are always <strong>angled</strong> and if you draw a line though the thinnest parts of the letters, you&rsquo;ll see that the <strong>stress is diagonal</strong>.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<blockquote>\r\n<p>Old Style typefaces are considered to be the best type for large amounts of body text on paper. That&rsquo;s why you&rsquo;ll find them used heavily in newspapers, magazines and books.</p>\r\n</blockquote>\r\n<p>Jennifer Farley, <a href=\"http://www.sitepoint.com/the-old-style-typeface/\">Site Point</a></p>','',1),(2,62,1,'','',2),(3,63,1,'','',3),(4,64,1,'','',4),(5,65,1,'','',5),(6,39,1,'','',6),(7,NULL,1,'','',7),(8,NULL,1,'','',8),(20,40,2,'','',4),(21,106,2,'','',5),(18,87,2,'','',2),(19,86,2,'','',3),(17,NULL,2,'<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/77ab3c3c3e33d574cc18aa7210733f1e.png\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Transitional typefaces represent the transition from Old Style to Modern style typefaces. Developed in the wake of the Enlightenment, transitional fonts were much less influenced by handwritten letterforms, emphasizing a <strong>greater differentiation between hairlines and stems </strong>and a more<strong> vertically oriented axis</strong>.</p>','',1),(15,NULL,1,'','',15),(16,NULL,1,'','',16),(13,NULL,1,'','',13),(14,NULL,1,'','',14),(11,NULL,1,'','',11),(12,NULL,1,'','',12),(9,NULL,1,'','',9),(10,NULL,1,'','',10),(22,107,2,'','',6),(23,NULL,2,'','',7),(24,NULL,2,'','',8),(25,NULL,3,'<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/cd7bb7622dc1e14553a041b6c4b427a1.gif\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>A term used to describe the typefaces designed at the end of the 18th C, these typefaces are generally characterized by vertical stress and horizontal hairline serifs. They have pronounced contrasts between thick and thin strokes. [Mechanical improvements in the printing press, better ink, and paper with more consistent printing surfaces allowed for such transitions.] Didot and Bodoni represent the first major fonts of this style. (Consuegra, <em>Classic Typefaces</em>)</p>','',1),(26,88,3,'','',2),(27,41,3,'','',3),(28,109,3,'','',4),(29,NULL,3,'','',5),(30,NULL,3,'','',6),(31,NULL,3,'','',7),(32,NULL,3,'','',8),(33,NULL,4,'<p><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/6c9e308a070e80fe3e7d9da4c6629aa5.gif\" alt=\"\" /></p>\r\n<p>Letterforms characterized by slab-like <strong>serifs similar in weight to the main strokes</strong>. They are also characterized by <strong>short descenders</strong>, and a number of features common to <em>Modern</em> typefaces. This style seems to be a product of the heightened interest in teh early ninetheeth century for all things that were Egyptian. (Consuegra,&nbsp;<em>Classic Typefaces</em>)</p>','',1),(34,89,4,'','',2),(35,90,4,'','',3),(36,91,4,'','',4),(37,42,4,'','',5),(38,110,4,'','',6),(39,NULL,4,'','',7),(40,NULL,4,'','',8),(41,NULL,4,'','',9),(42,43,5,'<p><span>Just exactly like what is sounds, a sans-serif typeface is a <strong>typeface without serifs</strong>. They can be found in history as early as the 5th century, although the classical revival of the Italian Renaissance return to old style serifed typefaces made them virtually obsolete until the 20th century. Their was much development of sans-serif typefaces in Germany as a revolt against the ornate lettering of the popular Blackletter styles which led to sans-serif typefaces based on the purity of geometric forms. Much like serifed typefaces, there are many different classifications for sans-serif typefaces. Below are listed the&nbsp;<span>British Standards Classification of Typefaces (BS 2961:1967)</span>:&nbsp;</span></p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><strong>Grotesque&nbsp;</strong>//&nbsp;Lineale typefaces with 19th-century origins. There is some contrast in thickness of strokes. They have squareness of curve, and curling close-set jaws. The R usually has a curled leg and the G is spurred. The ends of the curved strokes are usually horizontal.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Neo-Grotesque</strong>&nbsp;//&nbsp;Lineale typefaces derived from the grotesque. They have less stroke contrast and are more regular in design. The jaws are more open than in the true grotesque and the g is often open-tailed. The ends of the curved strokes are usually oblique.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Geometric</strong> //&nbsp;Lineale typefaces constructed on simple geometric shapes, circle or rectangle. Usually monoline, and often with single-storey a.</li>\r\n<li><strong>Humanist</strong>&nbsp;//&nbsp;Lineale typefaces based on the proportions of inscriptional Roman capitals and Humanist or Garalde lower-case, rather than on early grotesques. They have some stroke contrast, with two-storey a and g.</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p><span><span><span>(Source: Wikipedia,&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.designishistory.com/1450/type-classification/\">Design History</a>)</span></span></span></p>','<p>Neo-Grotesque</p>',1),(43,57,5,'','<p>Geometric</p>',2),(44,108,5,'','<p>Humanist</p>',3),(45,116,5,'','<p>Grotesque</p>',4),(46,115,5,'','<p>Neo-Grotesque</p>',5),(47,113,5,'','<p>Geometric</p>',6),(48,112,5,'','<p>Humanist</p>',7),(49,111,5,'','<p>Humanist</p>',8),(50,NULL,5,'','',9),(69,67,8,'<p><strong>Baseline</strong></p>\r\n<p>An imaginary horizontal line upon which all the letters rest, except the round letters, that usually go below this line somewhat.</p>','',1),(70,66,8,'<p><span><strong>Meanline</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>An imaginary line that marks the top of lowercase letter (a, c, e, g, i, j, m, n, o, r, s, x, y and z) and the top of the torso of letters (b, d, p, h and q).</span></p>','',2),(71,68,8,'<p><span><strong>X-Height</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>The basic vertical measurement of the body of a lowercase letter, without counting ascenders and descenders, and taking the letter x as a parameter (due to the fact that all four corners of the letter touch a point of measurement-i.e. baseline and mean line).</span></p>','',3),(72,69,8,'<p><span><strong>Cap Height</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>The cap height is the distance from the baseline to the top of uppercase letters like \'H\' and \'J.\'</span></p>','',4),(73,NULL,8,'','',5),(74,NULL,8,'','',6),(75,NULL,8,'','',7),(76,NULL,8,'','',8),(77,70,10,'<p><span><strong>Ascender</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>A vertical stroke that rises above the body of a lowercase letter, as found in letters b, d, f, h, k, l and t.</span></p>','',1),(78,71,10,'<p><span><strong>Descender</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>A vertical stem that extends below the baseline of a lowercase letter, as in the case of g, j, p, q, and y. In italic and calligraphic typefaces, we may find the letter f having a descender as well.</span></p>','',2),(79,72,10,'<p><span><strong>Serif</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>A term given to those characteristic stroke terminals normally found in Roman typefaces. Serifs may be unilateral (at only one side of the main stroke) or bilateral (at both sides).\"</span></p>','',3),(80,NULL,10,'','',4),(81,NULL,10,'','',5),(82,NULL,10,'','',6),(83,NULL,10,'','',7),(84,NULL,10,'','',8),(85,73,11,'<p><span><strong>Stem</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>A stem is main support of a letter. It is usually vertical or slightly inclined in italics. Curved letters do not have one.</span></p>','',1),(86,74,11,'<p><span><strong>Bar</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>The horizontal lines of an \"E\" are known as bars. Bars are horizontal or diagonal lines of a letter, also known as arms, and are open on at least one side.</span></p>','',2),(87,75,11,'<p><span><strong>Bowl</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>In a letter, it is a curved stroke which makes an enclosed space within a character, as in capital letters B, D P, R, and in lowercase letters a, b, g, p and q.</span></p>','',3),(88,76,11,'<p><span><strong>Counter space</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>Also called counter form, it is the inside opening or white area within a letter. Counter spaces may be closed in letters b,d,e,g,o,p and q, or partially open as in letters c, h, k, m, n, s, t, u, v, x, y and z. Letters like e and a, present both open and closed spaces.</span></p>','',4),(89,77,11,'<p><span><strong>Leg</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>The lower diagonal stroke, usually straight, in a letter, such as in K, k, and R.</span></p>','',5),(90,78,11,'<p><span><strong>Shoulder</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span><strong></strong>The stroke emerging from a stem, usually round, as in letters h, m and n.</span></p>','',6),(91,NULL,11,'','',7),(92,NULL,11,'','',8),(93,NULL,2,'','',9),(94,NULL,3,'','',9),(95,24,12,'<p><span>A website dedicated to typography and its history, notably featuring an interactive display of the fundamental aspects of the type anatomy.</span></p>','<p><a href=\"http://www.counterspace.us/typography/counterspace.swf\">Counter Space</a></p>',1),(96,118,12,'<p>An on-line companion to the book Thinking with Type: A Critical Guide for Designers, Writers, Editors, &amp; Students, by Ellen Lupton</p>','<p><a href=\"http://papress.com/thinkingwithtype/index.htm\">Thinking With Type</a></p>',2),(97,119,12,'<p><span>\"A quick and comprehensive type guide\"</span></p>','',3),(98,120,12,'<p><span>\"100% practical. Sketches have been made to explain some basic issues in type design during the workshops. They get used to point out some problems which raise while creating a new typeface. Only some foundations are shown, no deep sophisticated details.\"</span></p>','<p><a href=\"http://www.typeworkshop.com/index.php?id1=type-basics\">Typeworkshops.com</a></p>',4),(99,121,12,'<p><span>\"Type Topics is your source of information for important issues in typography today: everything from ampersands to OpenType&reg; technology.\"</span></p>','<p><a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/type/topics/index.html\">Adobe Type Topics</a>&nbsp;&amp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.adobe.com/type/topics/glossary.html\">Glossary</a></p>',5),(100,122,12,'<p><span>Typography.com\'s \"Learn\" section,&nbsp;</span>offers advice on from typographers&nbsp;Hoelfer and Frere-Jones..</p>','<p><a href=\"http://www.typography.com/ask/recentTopic.php?path=head\">Ask H&amp;FJ</a></p>',6),(101,123,12,'<p><span>\"Typography is an huge field. People devote years of their lives to this ancient craft, and yet there\'s always something new to learn. In this article, [Max Luzuriaga] reviews the major points that you should consider when selecting a typeface for a website.\"</span></p>','<p><a href=\"http://webdesign.tutsplus.com/articles/choosing-the-right-font-a-practical-guide-to-typography-on-the-web/\">Choosing the Right Font</a></p>',7),(102,124,12,'<p><span>Maria Popova, \"Brain Pickings\" author, describes 10 essential books on typography, ranging from the practical to the philosophical to the plain pretty.</span></p>','<p><a href=\"http://www.brainpickings.org/index.php/2011/08/01/10-essential-books-on-typography/\">10 Essential Books on Typography</a></p>',8),(103,NULL,12,'','',9),(104,NULL,12,'','',10),(105,NULL,12,'','',11),(106,NULL,12,'','',12),(116,129,14,'<p>Not much is known about Gutenberg\'s life. &nbsp;It is known that he was born in Meinz, Germany and soon moved to Strasburg before 1434. &nbsp;It was reported that he made metal mirrors for pilgrims visiting holy sites in the area. &nbsp;He used the first printing press using movable type to make his famous Bible in 1455. &nbsp;Not much more is known about Gutenberg except for the fact that he died in 1468.</p>\r\n<p>-Harry Ransom Center at University of Texas</p>','',1),(117,128,14,'','<p>Another portrait of Johannes Gutenberg</p>',2),(118,130,14,'','<p>Johannes Gutenberg\'s Bible</p>',3),(119,131,14,'','<p>Sample of the font type that Gutenberg used</p>',4),(120,NULL,14,'','',5),(121,NULL,14,'','',6),(122,NULL,14,'','',7),(123,NULL,14,'','',8),(124,NULL,14,'','',9),(125,NULL,5,'','',10),(126,NULL,5,'','',11),(127,NULL,5,'','',12),(128,NULL,2,'','',10),(129,NULL,2,'','',11),(130,NULL,2,'','',12),(131,NULL,3,'','',10),(132,NULL,3,'','',11),(133,NULL,3,'','',12),(134,NULL,4,'','',10),(135,NULL,4,'','',11),(136,NULL,4,'','',12),(411,NULL,42,'<p>As a quick glance through our site will hopefully reveal, we aimed to maintain a consistent aesthetic throughout our interface. Here Omeka and the \"Thanks, Roy\" theme proved our biggest obstacles:</p>\r\n<p>Interface Issues Specific to Exhibits</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Omeka\'s \"Thanks Roy\" theme was fitting for our minimalist aesthetic; however, as pictured to the right, it leaves much to be desired in way of nagivation, with exhibits presented in \"tab\" form (initially&nbsp;<em>without</em>&nbsp;boxed outlines) and sections listed in a disorienting jumble of hyperlinks.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>Its display of the sections themselves proved intitally problematic, as there was no way (aside from the limiting \"caption\" option) to spotlight a single image above a description of what it presented. This led to the discovery that adding aesthetic items such as headers or descriptive images to our Omeka database created a permanent link that could in turn be embedded into Omeka\'s alloted \"description\" areas using simple HTML.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Interface Issues for the Site as a Whole</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>There was no way for us to control the font, font size, or font color of the site. I resorted to photoshopping headers and banners for individual exhibits, but this resulted in some repetive titling.&nbsp;</li>\r\n<li>While Omeka sections came with a pre-set \"Gallery\" layout, a lot of our items were links and looked terrible in this format. We worked around this by taking screencaps of the sites we wanted to link (and labeling the images with a hyperlinked title of the site).</li>\r\n<li>Our theme came pre-set with several \"Browse\" features but we opted to override these and impose our own, customized menu in order to construct a stronger narrative. We felt this adapted menu was more appropriate for an audience of beginners. Our menu also features explicit numbering (i.e. 1. The Basics, 2. History, 3. Resources) to ensure that users, while free to roam the site as they please, know our intended ordering.&nbsp;</li>\r\n</ul>','',1),(153,126,17,'<p>Test your font recognition skills with this \"Rather Difficult\" Font Game.</p>','<p><a href=\"http://fontgame.ilovetypography.com\">The Rather Difficult Font Game</a></p>',1),(154,127,17,'<p>Humoursly ascribing letterforms with their respective personalities, this \"typographic dating game\" reveals the usually hidden layer of visual communication.&nbsp;</p>','<p><a href=\"http://papress.com/thinkingwithtype/the_personals/the_personals.htm\">The Personals</a></p>',2),(155,143,17,'<p>Shape Type: A letter shaping game</p>','<p><a href=\"http://shape.method.ac\">Shape Type</a></p>',3),(156,144,17,'<p>Kerntype: A Kerning Game</p>','<p><a href=\"http://type.method.ac\">Kern Type</a></p>',4),(157,NULL,17,'','',5),(158,NULL,17,'','',6),(159,NULL,17,'','',7),(160,NULL,17,'','',8),(161,NULL,17,'','',9),(162,NULL,17,'','',10),(163,NULL,17,'','',11),(164,NULL,17,'','',12),(165,61,18,'<p>\"Humanist, Old Style, Transitional, Modern,&nbsp;Slab Serif (Egyptian), Sans Serif--By the end of this six-part series, you will be quite&nbsp;<em>au fait</em>&nbsp;with all of these terms; and just imagine the joy you will experience when you proudly exclaim to the delight of your spouse, girlfriend, boyfriend, neighbor, guy at the corner shop,&nbsp;<em>Look at that Humanist inspired type! Note how the bar of the lowercase</em><span>&nbsp;\'</span><em>e\'</em><span>&hellip;.\"</span></p>','<p><a href=\"http://ilovetypography.com/2007/11/06/type-terminology-humanist-2/\">I Love Typography: Type History Series</a></p>',1),(166,125,18,'<p>This typography based section of \"Design is History\" provides a broad overview of salient issues.</p>','<p><a href=\"http://www.designishistory.com/design/typography/\">Design is History</a></p>',2),(167,85,18,'<p><span>Graphic designers will enrich their understanding of American type design and type designers with this unique and extensive reference. The fascinating history of type in America is chronicled through the typefaces and biographies of sixty-two of the most influential type designers, including Linn Boyd Benton, Morris Fuller Benton, and Darius Wells, and through the description and history of nine American type foundries.</span></p>','',3),(168,NULL,18,'','',4),(169,NULL,18,'','',5),(170,NULL,18,'','',6),(171,NULL,18,'','',7),(172,NULL,18,'','',8),(173,NULL,18,'','',9),(174,NULL,18,'','',10),(175,NULL,18,'','',11),(176,NULL,18,'','',12),(387,NULL,40,'<h3>For more details on how the following visualizations were creates, please read the <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/exhibits/show/methodology/syllabi\">Methodology Section</a>.</h3>\r\n<p><strong>First visualization</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/7a9042d557348e02014dda04a4c3e5e7.jpeg\"><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/7a9042d557348e02014dda04a4c3e5e7.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"100%\" /></a></p>\r\n<center>\r\n<p>Click image above to enlarge.</p>\r\n</center>\r\n<p><strong>Understianding the viz -</strong>&nbsp;This word cloud shows the analysis of 13 syllabi UCLA syllabi, which were 88 pages of text. At a glance &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Second Visualization:</strong>&nbsp;with this visualization, beyond the fact that it&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/f5e21388c49dff21a6d6f9be40c24ba4.jpeg\"><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/f5e21388c49dff21a6d6f9be40c24ba4.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"100%\" /></a></p>\r\n<center>\r\n<p>Click image above to enlarge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong><strong>Understianding the viz -</strong>&nbsp;</strong>This second word cloud analyzed a list of just under 400 resources found in the syllabi and the syllabi\'s respective websites.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>Third Visualization</strong>&nbsp;</p>\r\n</center>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/e60ec573e003a7e8a293eaf8732520e6.jpg\"><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/e60ec573e003a7e8a293eaf8732520e6.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"100%\" /></a></p>\r\n<center>\r\n<p>Click image above to enlarge.</p>\r\n</center>\r\n<p><strong>Understianding the viz -&nbsp;</strong>This bar graph shows the seven most common references used by DESMA professors when teaching typography at UCLA. For example&nbsp;<em>Getting It Right With Type</em>&nbsp;was only found in two syllabi.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Fourth Visualization</strong></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/57688fb4d59ae77b3b9beb904fb218a0.png\"><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/57688fb4d59ae77b3b9beb904fb218a0.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"100%\" /></a></p>\r\n<center>\r\n<p>Click image above to enlarge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;<strong>Understianding the viz -</strong> here we see the most complex analysis. I classified texts that were listed as \"Required\" and \"Suggested\" in Syllabi and assigned values of 2 and 1 respectively. The resulting visualization tries to show the most accurate depiction of how often textbooks are used by typography students based on syllabi.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n</center>','',1),(388,NULL,40,'<h2>For a more detailed description, see the <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/methods\">methodology</a>&nbsp;page.</h2>','',2),(177,NULL,12,'','',13),(178,NULL,12,'','',14),(179,NULL,12,'','',15),(185,NULL,17,'','',13),(186,NULL,17,'','',14),(187,NULL,17,'','',15),(188,NULL,17,'','',16),(180,NULL,12,'','',16),(181,NULL,18,'','',13),(182,NULL,18,'','',14),(183,NULL,18,'','',15),(184,NULL,18,'','',16),(205,145,20,'<p>John Baskerville was a printer and typeface innovator who was most known for his production of Milton\'s&nbsp;<em>Paradise Lost</em> and his Bible in 1763 which was regarded as his masterpiece. &nbsp;Benjamin Franklin was a great admirer of Baskerville and his typefaces, having many interactions with Baskerville over the course of his life. &nbsp;It wasn\'t until the 1920\'s when Baskerville\'s typefaces gained attention with the help of Bruce Rogers. &nbsp;(I Love Typography)</p>','',1),(206,NULL,20,'','',2),(207,114,20,'','<p>Example of Baskerville\'s typeface</p>',3),(208,156,20,'','<p>Title page of Milton\'s&nbsp;<em>Paradise Lost</em> created using Baskerville\'s printing press and utilizing his iconic typeface.</p>',4),(209,NULL,20,'','',5),(210,NULL,20,'','',6),(211,NULL,20,'','',7),(212,NULL,20,'','',8),(213,NULL,20,'','',9),(230,161,22,'<p>Relief printing involves the inking of a \"printing matrix.\" &nbsp;This matrix is usually composed of some sort of portruding design such as movable type. &nbsp;Paper is then placed on top of the matrix and pressed onto it using some sort of force. &nbsp;The portrusions then force the ink onto the paper and thus the image is then transferred onto the paper. &nbsp;This type of printing was the main form of printing from the time of Gutenberg all the way until the late 19th Century.</p>','<p>History Printing Press</p>',1),(214,176,21,'<p>As the virtual space of the web continues to corrode and replace traditional modes of cultural reproduction, the exigency for \"architects of the \'morrow\" reverberate throughout the globe. As a result, UCLA\'s&nbsp;Design and&nbsp;Media Arts department (DESMA) has seen terrific growth in the last decade in its curriculum -- from 13 classes in 2002 to 33 in 2012.&nbsp;Since its inception in January of 2005, DESMA 25 \"Typography\" has been taught 17 times. 13 of these 17 courses have a website full of inspiration, resources, and of course, a syllabus.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size: 1.17em;\"><br /></span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://classes.dma.ucla.edu/Winter12/25/nutrient.html\">Winter 2012</a>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://classes.dma.ucla.edu/Fall08/25/\">Fall 2008</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://classes.dma.ucla.edu/Spring11/25/\">Spring 2011</a>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://classes.dma.ucla.edu/Spring08/25/\">Spring 2008</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://classes.dma.ucla.edu/Winter11/25/\">Winter 2011</a>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<a href=\"http://classes.dma.ucla.edu/Winter08/25/\">Winter 2008</a></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://classes.dma.ucla.edu/Fall10/25/resources.html\">Fall 2010</a>&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; 