'',6),(248,NULL,23,'','',7),(249,NULL,23,'','',8),(250,NULL,23,'','',9),(251,NULL,23,'','',10),(252,NULL,23,'','',11),(253,NULL,23,'','',12),(254,174,24,'<p>Non-impact printing, as the name involves, does not involve physical plates or inked lettered surfaces touching paper but rather technologies such as inkjets or lasers creating impressions and letters in the paper by means of programmed functions via a computer. &nbsp;Tis type of printing offers many more options in terms of typography and much more flexibility in how one designs new designs for typefaces.</p>','<p>An Inkjet Printer</p>',1),(255,177,24,'','<p>A Laser Printer</p>',2),(256,178,24,'','<p>Diagram of how a laser printer works</p>',3),(257,179,24,'','<p>A Thermal Printer</p>',4),(258,NULL,24,'','',5),(259,NULL,24,'','',6),(260,NULL,24,'','',7),(261,NULL,24,'','',8),(262,NULL,24,'','',9),(263,NULL,24,'','',10),(264,NULL,24,'','',11),(265,NULL,24,'','',12),(266,97,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Sumerian Cuneiform Script</h2>\r\n<p>3000BC - 75</p>',1),(267,38,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Greek Capital Script</h2>\r\n<p>800BC - 100</p>',2),(268,96,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Roman Majiscule and Miniscule</h2>\r\n<p>100 - 600</p>',3),(269,36,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Roman Capital Alphabet</h2>\r\n<p>100 - 500</p>',4),(270,83,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Uncial Script</h2>\r\n<p>400 - 800</p>',5),(271,30,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Merovingian Script</h2>\r\n<p>700 - 900</p>',6),(272,34,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Visigothic Script</h2>\r\n<p>700 - 900</p>',7),(273,27,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Carolingian Minuscule</h2>\r\n<p>800 - 1200</p>',8),(274,84,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Old Italic Script</h2>\r\n<p>900 - 1300</p>',9),(275,94,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Gothic Script</h2>\r\n<p>1100 - 1500</p>',10),(276,95,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Rotunda</h2>\r\n<p>1500 - 1600</p>',11),(277,114,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Baskerville</h2>\r\n<p>1772</p>',12),(278,117,25,'','<h2 class=\"title\">Times New Roman</h2>\r\n<p>1931</p>',13),(279,NULL,25,'','',14),(280,NULL,25,'','',15),(281,NULL,25,'','',16),(389,NULL,40,'','',3),(390,NULL,40,'','',4),(391,NULL,40,'','',5),(392,NULL,40,'','',6),(393,NULL,40,'','',7),(394,NULL,40,'','',8),(395,182,41,'<p>Let me preface this account by stating I am in no way, shape or form a typography expert. Equipped with enthusiasm and a laptop, I decided to contruct the \"The Basics\" exhibit in response to my own frustration with the overwhelming quantity of information available online on the topic of typography. The more resources I aggregated, however, the more evident it became that <em>classification</em>&nbsp;within the topic of typography would be an issue. Within the field, there are a few different sets of attributes for classifying type, so I simply chose the set that I ran across most often: Oldstyle, Transitional, Modern, Slab Serif, Sans Serf.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Once the materials were collected, then came the problem of exhibiting it. Omeka\'s \"exhibit\" function presents information in a strictly heirarchal manner that forced us to split our information into specific sections. Creating an explicit narrative within each of the exhibits became incredibly important for us, for without it, the several levels could potentially confuse users. Our \"Search\" function allows for quick &nbsp;access a specific item, however, the nested structure resists quick and easy access to specific <em>pages</em>. Being such, we tried to make the information design easy enough to navigate so that users could easily--albeit not as quickly as a button on our home page-- find what they needed.</p>\r\n<p>Content wise, The Basics exhibit--it\'s \"Further resources\" section in particular--has huge potential for growth. While we focused more on letterforms than typography as a whole, our decision to ambitiously title the site \"Intro To <em>Typography</em>\" implies a hope that future students may contribute further to the work we have started.&nbsp;</p>','',1),(396,NULL,41,'','',2),(397,NULL,41,'','',3),(398,NULL,41,'','',4),(399,NULL,41,'','',5),(400,NULL,41,'','',6),(401,NULL,41,'','',7),(402,NULL,41,'','',8),(379,199,39,'<p>Ellen Lupton\'s&nbsp;<em>Typography with Style</em> came in as the <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/57688fb4d59ae77b3b9beb904fb218a0.png\">clear favorite across the 23 syllab</a>i sample. It\'s popularity is perhaps due to the availability of the resurce online, and it\'s clear presentation of typography and its components.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>\"Our all time best selling book is now available in a revised and expanded second edition.&nbsp;<em>Thinking with Type</em>&nbsp;is the definitive guide to using typography in&nbsp;visual communication, from the printed page to the computer screen. This revised edition includes forty-eight pages of new content, including the latest information on style sheets for print and the web, the use of ornaments and captions, lining and non-lining numerals, the use of small caps and enlarged capitals, as well as information on captions, font licensing, mixing typefaces, and hand lettering. Throughout the book, visual examples show how to be inventive within systems of typographic form&mdash;what the rules are and how to break them.&nbsp;<em>Thinking with Type</em>&nbsp;is a type book for everyone: designers, writers, editors, students, and anyone else who works with words. The popular online companion to&nbsp;<em>Thinking with Type</em>&nbsp;(www.thinkingwithtype.com) has been revised to reflect the new material in the second edition.\" (Source: <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Thinking-Type-2nd-revised-expanded/dp/1568989695/ref=sr_1_1?ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1355269657&amp;sr=8-1&amp;keywords=thinking+with+type\">Amazon.com</a>)</p>','',1),(380,198,39,'<p><em>Stop Stealing Sheep and Learn How Type Works</em> was the third most used book.</p>\r\n<p>\"This classic typography book, first published in 1993, is now updated with brand-new typefaces, fonts, and illustrations. Internationally renowned graphic designer Erik Spiekermann explains in everyday terms what typography is and offers design guidance in choosing type for legibility, meaning, and aesthetic appeal. Stop Stealing Sheep and Find Out How Type Works, 2nd Edition guides the reader through all aspects of typography, from the history and mechanics of type,&nbsp;<a id=\"_GPLITA_1\" title=\"Click to Continue &gt; by CouponDropDown\" href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Stop-Stealing-Sheep-Find-Works/dp/0201703394/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1355269916&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=stop+stealing+sheep#\">to training</a>&nbsp;the eye to recognize and choose typefaces. Uncover type\'s roots and placement within society and learn how to use space and layout to improve overall communication. This elegant guide for readers of all levels is revised and updated to discuss the particular design challenges of type on the Internet. Note: This title was originally announced in the October 2000 Pearson Technology Group catalog.\" (Source: <a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Stop-Stealing-Sheep-Find-Works/dp/0201703394/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1355269916&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=stop+stealing+sheep\">Amazon.com</a>)</p>','',2),(381,197,39,'<p><span><em>Elements of Typographic Style</em> was the second most used book from the sample. It\'s terse style (lacking almost any visuals) can seem unfriendly at first, epecially to such a visually sensitive user. It makes up this foible with keen descriptions and advice.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>\"Renowned typographer and poet Robert Bringhurst brings clarity to the art of typography with this masterful style guide. Combining the practical, theoretical, and historical, this edition is completely updated, with a thorough exploration of the newest innovations in intelligent font technology, and is a must-have for graphic artists, editors, or anyone working with the printed page using digital or traditional methods.\" (Source:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Elements-Typographic-Style-Robert-Bringhurst/dp/0881792063/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1355270119&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=elements+of+typographic+style\">Amazon.com</a>)</span></p>','',3),(382,196,39,'<p><em>Designing with Type:The Esential Guide to Typography</em> was tied for fourth most used book, but <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/57688fb4d59ae77b3b9beb904fb218a0.png\">what the data doesn\'t show</a>, is that it was used more frequently as a primary text, while the contender&nbsp;<em>Getting it Right With Type</em>, was more often used as an \"optional\" book.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;\"<span>The classic&nbsp;</span><em>Designing with Type</em><span>&nbsp;has been completely redesigned, with an updated format and full color throughout. New information and new images make this perennial best-seller an even more valuable tool for anyone interested in learning about typography. The fifth edition has been integrated with a convenient website, www.designingwithtype.com, where students and teachers can examine hundreds of design solutions and explore a world of typographic information. First published more than thirty-five years ago,&nbsp;</span><em>Designing with Type</em><span>&nbsp;has sold more than 250,000 copies&mdash;and this fully updated edition, with its new online resource, will educate and inspire a new generation of designers.\"&nbsp;(Source:&nbsp;<a href=\"http://www.amazon.com/Designing-Type-5th-Essential-Typography/dp/0823014134/ref=sr_1_1?s=books&amp;ie=UTF8&amp;qid=1355270563&amp;sr=1-1&amp;keywords=designing+with+type%3Athe+essential+guide+to+typography\">Amazon.com</a>)</span></p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',4),(383,NULL,39,'','',5),(384,NULL,39,'','',6),(385,NULL,39,'','',7),(386,NULL,39,'','',8),(306,158,30,'<p>Jan Tschicold was born on April 2, 1902 in Leipzig, Germany. &nbsp;He was a leading advocate in Modernist design and non-centered design. &nbsp;He condemned all typefaces except sans-serif and created his own manifesto on the principles of design. &nbsp;He well known for popularizing the Van der Graaf canon which is used in book design to divide pages into pleasing proportions. &nbsp;Towards the later part of his life, Tschicold gradually shifted back to Classicsm rejecting his more Modernist principles. &nbsp;Some of his famous typefaces include Sabon and Saskia. &nbsp;He is probably most well known for his work at Penguin Books where he created the well known standard book cover that can be seen even today.</p>','',1),(307,160,30,'','<p>Sabon, a font designed by Tschichold using a modernist artistic style.</p>',2),(308,159,30,'','<p>The popular Penguin Book cover design created by Tschichold himself</p>',3),(309,NULL,30,'','',4),(310,NULL,30,'','',5),(311,NULL,30,'','',6),(312,NULL,30,'','',7),(313,NULL,30,'','',8),(314,NULL,30,'','',9),(371,NULL,37,'<p>I undertook the ambitious project of creating an exhibit that showcases a very brief and very overarching summary of the historical roots of Western typography. &nbsp;I decided to seperate the exhibit into three sections to help easy navigation throughout the exhibit and to help make sure that the user was not overwhelmed with links and pages. &nbsp;The three secitions are labeled \"People,\" \"Technology,\" and \"Historical Fonts.\" &nbsp;In my opinion, these classifications are appropriate because they offer the user three main areas of focus that, as a whole, help illustrate the overal development of typography, and not just the development of different typefaces. &nbsp;On each page, I chose 3 or 4 different objects that, in my opinion, most exemplifies the sections message, constituting the narrative purpose of the page. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The \"People\" section is comprised of 3 pages, each highlighting a different person who contributed to major transional periods in the development of Western typography. &nbsp;I chose to pick the persons based on about 200 year intervals because this seemed to make a more consistent narrative. The \"Technologies\" portion of the&nbsp;exhibit, portrays different examples of three different technological processes.&nbsp; Although these technologies are not spaced out in consistent intervals like the \"People\" section, I chose these different technological innovations based on the popularity of the techniques throughout the course of typography\'s evolution.&nbsp; I decided to add the \"Historical Font\" section with the help of Mateusz in order to give a different level of understanding to typography\'s narrative in that it did not just start with Gutenberg.&nbsp; The art of writing script has been around for thousands of years, and we wanted to represent that in some way.</p>','',1),(372,NULL,37,'','',2),(373,NULL,37,'','',3),(374,NULL,37,'','',4),(375,NULL,37,'','',5),(376,NULL,37,'','',6),(377,NULL,37,'','',7),(378,NULL,37,'','',8),(327,195,32,'<p>Although finding any document is often a google search away, it seems that instructors are recalcitrant to share their syllabus. Yet, as typography continues to cater more and more to web design curricula, these classes often have an accompanying website from, whichpresumably adds a layer of communication, information, and familiarity for the students.</p>\r\n<p>These are some of the Syllabi found at other educational insititutions:</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',1),(328,194,32,'','',2),(329,193,32,'','',3),(330,192,32,'','',4),(331,191,32,'','',5),(332,190,32,'','',6),(333,189,32,'','',7),(334,188,32,'','',8),(335,187,32,'','',9),(336,186,32,'','',10),(337,NULL,32,'','',11),(338,NULL,32,'','',12),(339,148,33,'<p>One of the early decisions in the design of the Neatline exhibit was choosing whether to georeference items by<strong> city</strong> or <strong>country</strong>. Most older historical fonts have obscure origins; we only know what nation they originate from. Meanwhile, the origins of modern fonts can be easily traced to specific cites. At first, I was going to create a hybrid exhibit where historical fonts were georeferenced as colored regions (corresponding to their <strong>country</strong> of origin) while modern fonts where georeferenced to their known <strong>city</strong> of origin. However, this created a number of issues:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>This map was inconsistant and biased. Historical fonts had more siginificance because they occupied entire regions, while modern fonts only occupied points.</li>\r\n<li>National borders are not constant throughout history, so using modern national borders to depict historical fonts was completely illogical. For example, we used the region of modern Italy to represent the Roman Capital Alphabet, but the Roman Empire was much larger in its time.</li>\r\n<li>By correlating fonts to specific regions, one implies that the font was used everywhere in that region and nowhere else. However, most historical fonts were used outside of their country of origin.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Therefore, we chose to georeference all fonts to their <strong>city</strong> of origin, while fonts with obscure origins where georeferenced to the capital of their <strong>country</strong> of origin. This gives unbiased representation of all fonts, both modern and historical. However, there is still one major problem: By georeferencing obscure fonts to their national capital, we imply that they were actually created at the capital.</p>','<p><strong>An early design of the Neatline exhibit</strong></p>',1),(340,NULL,33,'','',2),(341,NULL,33,'','',3),(342,NULL,33,'','',4),(343,NULL,33,'','',5),(344,NULL,33,'','',6),(345,NULL,33,'','',7),(346,NULL,33,'','',8),(347,151,34,'<p>The central challenge in choosing the base layer is balancing practicality with visual appeal. Originally, I was going to use the&nbsp;<strong>Stamen Toner</strong>&nbsp;base layer because it contained the right amount of data for our discussion. This base layer was the most practical because the only information it shows is national borders, country names, and major cities. However, &nbsp;this base layer is not very appealing visually, and it obsures some of the items presented (circled in red).</p>','<h2>\"Stamen Toner\"</h2>',1),(348,150,34,'<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Open Street Map</strong>&nbsp;base layer was neither practical nor visually appealling. The details shown on the map have no relevance to our discussion of typography and the white landmasses also obscure some of the exhibits. Therefore, the Open Street Map was the first to be eliminated from our choice of base layers.</p>','<h2>\"Open Street Map\"</h2>',2),(349,149,34,'<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Google Satellite</strong>&nbsp;base layer is very appealing&nbsp;visually because all of the items are clearly visible on the map. However, there are no borders or cities labelled on the map, which may confuse users unfamiliar with the geography of Europe. Therefore, this base layer, despite its beauty, was not very practical for our purposes.</p>','<h2>\"Google Satellite\"</h2>',3),(350,152,34,'<p>The most visually appealing base layer is&nbsp;<strong>Stamen Watercolor.</strong>&nbsp;Its unique, tea-stained design fits well with our typography theme. However, this base layer does not have enough contrast between the items and the map itself; the items stand out, but they are not as sharply contrasted as they were in the Google Satellite base layer. Also, the lack of borders and labelled countries made Stamen Watercolor an impractical choice for our base layer.&nbsp;</p>','<h2>\"Stamen Watercolor\"</h2>',4),(351,149,34,'<p>Finally, we decided to use&nbsp;<strong>Google Hybrid</strong>&nbsp;as the base layer for the Neatline exhibit because it provides a fair balance between visual appeal and practicality. The geographical data is irrelevant to our discussion, but the green terrain makes the items clearly visible. Also, countries, borders, and major cities are clearly labelled for user reference. Despite our choice of the default base layer, the user still has the option to change the base layer while viewing the exhibit. This is why visual appeal took precedence over practicality in our choice; the default map greets the user with an accessible view of the exhibit, but then the user can change the base layer to a more practical view (like Stamen Toner) when making a more practical analysis.</p>','<h2>\"Google Hybrid\"</h2>',5),(352,NULL,34,'','',6),(353,NULL,34,'','',7),(354,NULL,34,'','',8),(355,157,35,'<h2>Temporal Scaling</h2>\r\n<p>Neatline is very limited in the choice of scale for a timeline. Our data ranges from 3000 BC to the present, but the farthest that we can zoom out on our timeline is by century. If Neatline offered a \"millenia\" Context Band Unit, then the user could have had a more comprehensive view of our timeline. Ideally, I would have used a logarithmic timeline to represent our data, but Neatline does not offer this feature. A logarithmic timeline is ideal for this type of data set because we have a huge temporal range with most of the data clustered in the earlier dates. However, the Neatline timeline does not have the bias that is inherent in a logarthmic timeline, so it does offer a more literal perception of the history of typography.</p>','<p>The&nbsp;<strong>Context Band Unit</strong>&nbsp;sets the scale of our timeline</p>',1),(356,154,35,'<h2>Spatial Scaling</h2>\r\n<p>One major problem with Neatline is that there is no way to adjust how far the application zooms in on the map when an item is selected from the item list on the right. This implies that the font was created at a specific address, but we only know the city where it was created. The most recent version of the Neatline application has a feature under styling that allows designers to set the map zoom, but this feature was absent from our older version.</p>','<p>Sabon was invented in this backyard?</p>',2),(357,NULL,35,'','',3),(358,NULL,35,'','',4),(359,NULL,35,'','',5),(360,NULL,35,'','',6),(361,NULL,35,'','',7),(362,NULL,35,'','',8),(363,167,36,'<p>One purpose of the Nealtine exhibit is to give the user a global perspective of the development of typography. The point graphics for each font give the user a quick visual reference of each font on the map. The default map zoom ensures the visibility of all fonts that we have plotted on our map of the world. Although this view gives the user a global perspective, there is no way to make the items smaller when zoomed out; they have the same size at all zoom levels. This is why the map looks so cluttered from a zoomed out perspective.</p>','<p>The Defualt Map Zoom of the Neatline Exhibit</p>',1),(364,163,36,'<p>As we zoom in over Europe, we begin to see how different fonts originated in different countries, but fonts from the same countries are still very cluttered. This, along with the size of the item image, makes it difficult to tell in which part of the country an individual font originated.</p>','<p>Zooming in over Europe</p>',2),(365,165,36,'<p>When we zoom in over country, we can see which city the fonts originated from. However, when multiple fonts originate from the same city, the point graphics overlap and obscure one another.</p>','<p>Zooming in over France</p>',3),(366,166,36,'<p>Once we zoom in all the down to the maximum, we can see all the fonts that originated in a city. To make this view possible, I plotted fonts slightly apart from each other to keep them from overlapping at this zoom level. This zoom level is also the defualt zoom level when user clicks on a item in the item list on the right hand side of the exhibit. With this view, the user can click on a font, then see all of the other fonts that originated from that city.</p>','<p>All of the fonts from Paris</p>',4),(367,NULL,36,'','',5),(368,NULL,36,'','',6),(369,NULL,36,'','',7),(370,NULL,36,'','',8),(412,NULL,43,'<p><strong>My first attempt</strong> to extrapolate interesting information out of the 13 DESMA syllabi was through a word cloud in <em>Many Eyes</em>&gt;. After collecting the text from all the syllabi (with the help of OCR), I analyzed the resulting 88 pages for word frequency. The result was uninteresting.</p>\r\n<p><br /> <br /> <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/7a9042d557348e02014dda04a4c3e5e7.jpeg\"><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/7a9042d557348e02014dda04a4c3e5e7.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"100%\" /></a></p>\r\n<center>\r\n<p>Click image above to enlarge.</p>\r\n</center>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>The issue</strong> with this visualization, beyond the fact that it doesn\'t give any quantitative relations, is that it barely furthers our understanding of what the a Typography syllabus has to offer. I came to the conclusion that this specialized documents requires close reading and structured data.</p>\r\n<p>I started the<strong> second attempt</strong> by considering classifications for a simple mark-up of the syllabi. Unfortunately, the content covered each week in class, the assignments, and the major projects, were almost identical across the 13 documents, lowering significantly the energy vs. interesting outcome yield. There only interesting differences were in the reference materials, ie. textbooks used.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>The third attempt</strong> focused on transferring the reference materials: texts, required readings, etc. onto a file for another word cloud analysis. Here we see&nbsp;<span>a list of just under 400 resources found in the syllabi and the syllabi\'s respective websites. As most syllabi had a lot of reference materials and content on a website, I chose to include all the resources to see whther there where any emergent patterns.</span></p>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/f5e21388c49dff21a6d6f9be40c24ba4.jpeg\"><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/f5e21388c49dff21a6d6f9be40c24ba4.jpeg\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"100%\" /></a></p>\r\n<center>\r\n<p>Click image above to enlarge.</p>\r\n</center>\r\n<p><strong>&nbsp;The issue</strong> with this visualization is that once again, it offers little information. We do see a few names repeated though: Ellen, Lupton, Spiekermann, Erik, Bringhurst. These are authors names, which is a great start, but as nothing is quantified, there is a need for a more specific distinction between the data (more structures), and a more illustrative visualization.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This led me to a <strong>fourth attempt</strong>. Here, I took only the primary references in syllabi. I did away with the companion website\'s lists of resources, and designated the texts that were slassified by the instructors in the syllabi as \"required\", the value of \"primary resources\". I then transcribed all these primary resources onto an excel sheet, sorted the titles alphabetically, and then displayed the frequency of each title.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<center>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/e60ec573e003a7e8a293eaf8732520e6.jpg\"><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/e60ec573e003a7e8a293eaf8732520e6.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"100%\" /></a></p>\r\n<center>\r\n<p>Click image above to enlarge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>The issue </strong>in this bar graph is the classification. Including only the primary resources is misleading, although it is true that these are the seven most common references used by DESMA professors when teaching typography at UCLA, it does not factor in the \"optional\" or \"reccomended\" readings. My concern was that these secondary resources would turn out to be books that were assigned very often, thus skewing this graph\'s veracity.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">I launched my <strong>final attempt</strong>&nbsp;to illustrate \"the most commonly used resources in Typography classes\" by taking into account both the primary and the secondary resources. At this point i was left with very little data, so I decided to incorporate some other syllabi I had been collecting. This introduction made for a more varied sample, but included some differences that rendered a comparison somewhat questionable. There was an issue of the duration of the class, from 10 to 18 weeks, to the level/quality of the insitutions: state university, research universities, art schools, which affected more than in a few ways what the data shows. Perhaps these differences could be resolved with a drastic increase in scale -- the statistical relevance could then negate these issues, given the parameter \"Influence of books on students of typography classes\".</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">Not knowing how much exposure these texts have had in each class, I opted to distinguish their relevance by attributing an arbitrary value. The primary texts were assigned 2 points, while the secondary were given 1 point. The result were the following:</p>\r\n</center>\r\n<p><a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/57688fb4d59ae77b3b9beb904fb218a0.png\"><img src=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/archive/files/57688fb4d59ae77b3b9beb904fb218a0.png\" alt=\"\" width=\"100%\" height=\"100%\" /></a></p>\r\n<center>\r\n<p>Click image above to enlarge.</p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\">There were still some&nbsp;<strong>issues with this data</strong>&nbsp;as well:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">The classification of Primary versus Secondary data vis-a-vis the bar chart can really change the message of the visualization. When I tried a 3:1 or 5:1 ratio. When increasing the ration there were two noticeable changes: the tying&nbsp;<em>Designing with Type</em> and&nbsp;<em>Getting it Right with Type</em> broke their tie, but the second change was drastic:&nbsp;<em>Thinking with type</em>&nbsp;dwarfed everything else, and made it appear to be much more important than anyhting else. The differences between the other bars were minimized as well. I chose to go with a 2:1 ratio as to avoid a skewed visualization.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong><br /></strong></p>\r\n<p style=\"text-align: left;\"><strong>General Issues with the data&nbsp;</strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li style=\"text-align: left;\">Professors that taught more than once and who used the same texts were included in the data. This adversely affects the data as these &ldquo;duplicates&rdquo; made the data less accurate. But it also serves some purpose, it indicates the relative <strong>influence of a textbook per student</strong>. The difference between these two questions could be explored in a longer project, and directed by the following questions: how influential are these books? Versus: how often are these books being used by professors?</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div style=\"text-align: left;\">&nbsp;</div>\r\n<center>\r\n<p>Special Thanks to Iman for setting such a high bar for quality and leading the for excellent aesthetics.&nbsp;</p>\r\n</center></center></center>','',1),(413,NULL,44,'<h2><strong style=\"font-size: 10px;\">Omeka</strong></h2>\r\n<p>Access to Omeka from off-campus requires a VPN installation. This was the first of many technical issues I, and many others had (strangely, some didn\'t find that to be an issue, but rather a part of the process).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I now know that Computer Science, programming languages, and web design all share a kind of organizational logic. These hierarchies ARE NOT always explicit or intuitive, so figuring out how Omeka worked required lots of trial and error, and/or help.</p>\r\n<p>Another issue was the limitations of Omeka. We wanted a better aesthetic, so we tried incorporating more aesthetic components into the exhibits and interface, but the only was to do so was to upload the images to the site as &ldquo;&rsquo;items&rdquo;. As we did not want these items to be seen as part of our items page, we made them \"Not Public\". This seemed like an easy solution, but as it turns out it\'s all or nothing with OMeka. Either it can be seen and clicked on to find out all the relevant information about the item, which is not the purpose of a thumbnail pic used for aesthetics and readability, or no one can see it. Once again Omeka proved to be unintuitive.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>HTML</strong></p>\r\n<p>Becoming familiar with HTML was a first for me. Although I couldn\'t follow completely conversaitons like \"ya, just insert your link into the href field\", I managed to scrape by mostly through imitation and observation of other\'s code.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>MS Word &amp; Excel, Many Eyes, Acrobat Pro, and other quirks</strong></p>\r\n<p>Again, not being familiar with some basics such as how to delete a specific word from a&nbsp;<strong>Word</strong>&nbsp;document, can lead to a very humanist experience: frustration and exasperation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This was equally true for&nbsp;<strong>Many Eyes</strong>: Chrome doesn\'t support Java 7, which is necessary for some visualizations in Many Eyes, so I had to download Firefox and work from there. I never figured ou the issue, but the visualization toolbar options worked only when they wanted, for example, the \"Banning\" certian words from te visualization, never worked. Ironically this led me to the hiccup with Word.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br /> Excel</strong>: I had the luck of having Dr. Perry, my Anthropology Professor, show us how she processes data from her Capuchin focal-follows. This is how I learned Excel 2 weeks ago. Once again, I felt like simple tasks like making an excel sheet, was long and full of errors, which were remedied by the amateur tutorial on Youtube.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Acrobat</strong>: I got a hold of the Acrobat Pro application to resolve an issue with two DESMA syllabi: they had been uploaded to their respective sites as pictures instead of .doc or .pdf. My girlfriend procured me with a copy and showed a magical tool: OCR -- it\'s incredible!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><strong>Other Quirks</strong><strong>&nbsp;</strong><strong></strong></p>\r\n<p>Because of the quantity of applications, number of tabs open in browsers, on my computer, my entry-level MacBook from 2007 stalled more than a few times. I\'m incredulous it didn\'t melt on my lap mid type -- the fan has been at full-force since I started the project. Thankfully I had the insides of my computer upgraded by a professional last summer.</p>\r\n<p>Being my first project of scale with a computer, I found myself cluttering my desktop with files. This led me to an increased knowledge of my OS system, but also Activity Monitor, and Terminal (the latter mostly because of RAM issues related to processing overload, and large quantities of open apps and documents).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',1),(414,NULL,44,'<h2>Omeka</h2>\r\n<p>Access to Omeka from off-campus requires a VPN installation. This was the first of many technical issues I, and many others had (strangely, some didn\'t find that to be an issue, but rather a part of the process).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>I now know that Computer Science, programming languages, and web design all share a kind of organizational logic. These hierarchies ARE NOT always explicit or intuitive, so figuring out how Omeka worked required lots of trial and error, and/or help.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',2),(415,NULL,44,'<h2>MS Word &amp; Excel, Many Eyes, Acrobat Pro, and other quirks</h2>\r\n<p>Again, not being familiar with some basics such as how to delete a specific word from a <strong>Word</strong> document, can lead to a very humanist experience: frustration and exasperation.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>This was equally true for <strong>Many Eyes</strong>: Chrome doesn\'t support Java 7, which is necessary for some visualizations in Many Eyes, so I had to download Firefox and work from there. I never figured ou the issue, but the visualization toolbar options worked only when they wanted, for example, the \"Banning\" certian words from te visualization, never worked. Ironically this led me to the hiccup with Word.</p>\r\n<p><strong><br /></strong><strong>Excel</strong>: I had the luck of having Dr. Perry, my Anthropology Professor, show us how she processes data from her Capuchin focal-follows. This is how I learned Excel 2 weeks ago. Once again, I felt like simple tasks like making an excel sheet, was long and full of errors.</p>\r\n<p><strong>Acrobat</strong>: I got a hold of the Acrobat Pro application to resolve an issue with two DESMA syllabi: they had been uploaded to their respective sites as pictures instead of .doc or .pdf. My girlfriend procured me with a copy of Acrobat Pro and showed me how to use the OCR option -- it\'s incredible!</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',3),(416,NULL,44,'<h2>Other Quirks<span style=\"font-size: 10px;\">&nbsp;</span></h2>\r\n<p>Because of the quantity of applications, number of tabs open in browsers, on my computer, my entry-level MacBook from 2007 stalled more than a few times. I\'m incredulous it didn\'t melt on my lap mid type -- the fan has been at full-force since I started the project. Thankfully I had the insides of my computer upgraded by a professional last summer.</p>\r\n<p>Being my first project of scale with a computer, I found myself cluttering my desktop with files. This led me to an increased knowledge of my OS system, but also Activity Monitor, and Terminal (the latter mostly because of RAM issues related to processing overload, and large quantities of open apps and documents).</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',4),(417,NULL,44,'<h2>&nbsp;</h2>','',5),(418,NULL,44,'','',6),(419,NULL,44,'','',7),(420,NULL,44,'','',8),(421,NULL,45,'<p><strong><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\">Metadata</span></strong></p>\r\n<p>In terms of our metadata, we decided to show the object\'s Title, Subject, Description, Creator, Source, Date, and Contributor.&nbsp; We came to the conclusion that these categories best expressed an objects context and gave the user a decent image as to what they were looking and why it was important.&nbsp; However, even though we felt that these categories were sufficient to convey an objects relevance and context, we also felt that the metadata provided by Dublin Core through Omeka left a lot to be desired. First of all, the actual action of entering information into each Dublin Core field quickly became tedious and, to a point, redundant. &nbsp; The fact that items from a single site could not be mainstreamed and have an autofill option for the fields created the obstacle of time and inconsistency. &nbsp;Some objects would be labeled as coming from a different source due to human error, and one would have to go back and the source title. &nbsp;Second of all, Omeka should have the option of directly downloading an object from the source. &nbsp;This would limit the level of mediation in terms of the object itself. &nbsp;By having to save the object onto our own devices and then uploading it to Omeka, we are adding another level of mediation between the original source and creator of the object and the final product of what we are showing. &nbsp;This, in turn, actually can make the metadata quite confusing since, by uploading it to Omeka, we thus become a contributer to the object. &nbsp;Also the actual size of the object may change when saving and uploading as well. &nbsp;This is one of the main reasons that we chose not to show the size of the uploaded object. &nbsp;There is is simply no way of knowing if the size that is recorded on the source is the actual size that has been uploaded to Omeka.</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Classification</strong></span></p>\r\n<p>In dealing with our classification system, we seperated our items into four main collections: Typefaces, History of Typography, Typography &amp; Letterforms (DESMA 25) Syllabi, and Educational Resources. We chose these classifications for our collections primarily for the frequency of those object types appearing and because of the functionality of these classifications. &nbsp;First off all, in the gathering of our items, we notices that a bulk of the items were made up of things that constituted typefaces and educational resources that could be found on the web. &nbsp;The yllabi data visualization also created two unique types of objects that seemed to proliferate the entire object list. &nbsp;Next, we also considered functionality in our collection classification. &nbsp;For users, who we are assuming are interested in the topic of typography. &nbsp;We believe that examples of typefaces, as well as items that make up different elements of typography\'s history will successfully allow the user to explore basic concepts of typography and find different elements of what typography is comprised of. &nbsp;The syllabi collection offers itself as a category of investigation for more invested users. &nbsp;In this collections, users can investigate how typography is being studied in the field of academia and how educational institutions are approaching such a study. The educational resources is for users who wish to continue on with learning about typography and immerse themselves more in the topic. &nbsp;We sort of wanted to position it as an appropriate conclusion to our narrative. &nbsp;</p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><strong>Tagging</strong></span></p>\r\n<p><span style=\"text-decoration: underline;\"><br /></span>We wanted to choose tags that would not be redundant to the different subject headers of the objects and that would connect different types of objects to each other. &nbsp;We wanted the tags to convey the functionality of the object beyond what the collection that it was classified under. &nbsp;We also wanted to convey the messages that many of these objects can be used to advance the same narrative or, in a sense, can work together in order to provide a more layered knowledge.</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>','',1),(422,184,46,'<p>Most of these syllabi use a similar format. Sure, UCLA\'s syllabi covers only 10 weeks while other syllabi can cover 16 or even 18 weeks, nevertheless meaningful data can still arise. By using some tools of analysis such as a word cloud or simple bar visualizations, you can clearly see that most of these classes use the same handful of textbooks. For example, Ellen Lupton\'s&nbsp;<em>Thinking With Type</em> is a favorite that should be the \"go-to\" resource for any curious student of type, typefonts, and typography.</p>\r\n<p>My best assessment produced the following ranking:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li><em>Thinking with Type: A Critical Guide for Designers, Writers, Editors, &amp; Students</em> by&nbsp;Ellen Lupton</li>\r\n<li><em>The Elements of Typographic Style</em> by&nbsp;Robert Bringhurst</li>\r\n<li><em><em>Stop Stealing Sheep &amp; Find Out How Type Works</em>&nbsp;by<em>&nbsp;</em>Erik Spiekermann&nbsp;</em></li>\r\n<li><em>Getting it Right With Type:&nbsp;The Dos and Don\'ts of Typography</em> by Victoria Squire</li>\r\n<li><em>Designing with Type:The Essential Guide to Typography</em> by&nbsp;James Craig</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>To see more data, plese <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/exhibits/show/resources/process\">click here</a>, or click on the tab entitled \"with visualizations\".</p>','<p>A screen capture from Lupton\'s syllabi outline, found on <a href=\"http://papress.com/other/thinkingwithtype/teachers/teacher_home.htm\">her site</a>.</p>',1),(423,NULL,46,'','',2),(424,NULL,46,'','',3),(425,NULL,46,'','',4),(426,NULL,46,'','',5),(427,NULL,46,'','',6),(428,NULL,46,'','',7),(429,NULL,46,'','',8),(439,NULL,49,'<p>Neatline offers a number of different ways for designers to select which items will show up in their Neatline exhibit. There are various categories to choose from, such as the collection, user (who added the item), or even its type. Originally, I was going to make the query present all the items in the \"History of Typography\" collection. However, this brought about two issues:</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>Some of the items in the collection are not fonts, but would show up on the timeline anyway.</li>\r\n<li>I later chose to add modern fonts to the exhibit, but these were in another collection.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>The main problem with using any category as the query for a Neatline exhibit is that these categories are not static. If an item is moved from one collection to another, or if the item type is revised, then the item might not show up in the exhibit anymore. Likewise, other items may show up inintentionally.</p>\r\n<p>Therefore, I chose to use tagging for my Neatline query. For every item that I wanted to add to my timeline, I simply gave it a&nbsp;<a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/items/tags\">\"timeline\"</a>&nbsp;tag. Then, I made the Neatline query display all items with the <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/items/tags\">\"timeline\"</a>&nbsp;tag. This simple solution is very effective because the <a href=\"http://dh101.humanities.ucla.edu/DH101Fall12Lab1/items/tags\">\"timeline\"</a>&nbsp;tag is independant of any other classification systems in our database. My fellow designers could then move items from one collection to another without disrupting the content of the Neatline exhibit.</p>','',1),(440,NULL,50,'<h2><strong>Audience Design</strong></h2>\r\n<p>The &ldquo;Resources&rdquo; exhibit was designed with two concerns in mind:</p>\r\n<ol>\r\n<li>Representing the essence of a digital humanities project</li>\r\n<li>Presenting a learning resource for anyone that wants to learn typography</li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>Most digital humanities projects serve scholars, but I believe digital humanities projects can maintain their venerable standards while adopting better methodological components -- especially when it comes to projects in the vein of social sciences.</p>\r\n<p>For example Wikipedia is in many ways is a very successful Digital Humanities project, where instead of scholars generating &ldquo;digital objects&rdquo;, we find common users creating and editing information known as \"pages\". Sure there are plenty of issues with this type of open-source method, but it also offers some solutions about sustainability and preservation of digital humanities projects. The most alluring part of this kind of collaboration is the knowledge base and labor that common users can provide to the advancement of the project (not to mention the pecuniary power! Again, Wikipedia).&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>The <a href=\"http://www.fastionline.org/about.php?view=aboutfasti\">FASTI Online</a> project takes this collaborative stance, and I have a hunch that that a large part of the future projects in the Digital Humanities will expand and make use of this collaborative methodology with its unconventional contributors. An alternative pattern could be that the influence of digital humanities on the rest of the academia will see these types of collaborative projects emerge from the social science fields directly.&nbsp;</p>\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n<h2><strong>Interface</strong></h2>\r\n<p>I opted not to use numbers in the Exhibit tabs in the hopes that readers would slow down a bit and read a little between the lines. It&rsquo;s a technique advocated by Kirshenbaum and others in the digital humanities field. I tried to repair the fluidity and clarity of the navigation by using a more commercial feel, much like a website. I understand this can be frowned upon, but I think it is necessary for the users of this site.&nbsp;</p>','',1),(441,155,51,'<p>Neatline offers the option of having an item list aside from the map and the timeline. This feature can be omitted, but I found it useful as a quick reference to the items in the exhibit. It may be difficult for users to find a specific font if they do not know where or when it originated. Ideally, I would have designed the item list with hierarchical categories where each font is grouped with the other fonts of its class. This way, the item list would not require that much scrolling (since it contains 40 items). However, Neatline does not have this feature. Therefore, I chose to list the items in alphabetical order so that the users can quickly scroll down to any fonts that they are familiar with. In the end, I found this system to be much more intuitive for users who are not be familiar with font classification systems.</p>','<p>The most simple solution is often the most effective.</p>',1),(442,NULL,51,'','',2),(443,NULL,51,'','',3),(444,NULL,51,'','',4),(445,NULL,51,'','',5),(446,NULL,51,'','',6),(447,NULL,51,'','',7),(448,NULL,51,'','',8),(449,201,52,'<h2>Historical vs. Modern Fonts</h2>\r\n<p>A central challenge to designing the timeline portion of the Neatline exhibit was accounting for the disparity in the accuracy of our data. We can trace the origins of modern fonts to a specific year, but the origins of historical fonts are often more ambiguous. Instead of having a specific date for their origin, we have a range of when they were used. To show this disparity on the timeline, modern fonts with known dates of origin are represented by points while historical fonts have a range corresponding to when they were used.</p>\r\n<h2>Technical Challenges</h2>\r\n<p>The Nealtine application is very unintuitive when inputing dates. At first, none of the historical dates were appearing on the timeline. Why?</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li>BC dates have to be inputed with a negative sign. 3000 BC must be typed as \"-3000\"</li>\r\n<li>all dates must have four digits. 100 AD must be typed as \"0100\"</li>\r\n</ul>','<p>Some items are represented by points while others are given a range.</p>',1);
